a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real and f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x = 1 / (abs(x powr 2 - 6*x + 8) + abs(x powr 2 + x - 6))"
shows  "x \<noteq> 2"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 What real values of $x$ are not in the domain of

$f(x)=\frac{1}{|x^2-6x+8|+|x^2+x-6|}$? The final Answer is 2
 ### Proof
 $x$ is not in the domain of $f$ if the denominator is zero. Since both absolute values are nonnegative, both must be zero for the denominator to be zero.
 So \begin{align} 0&=x^2-6x+8=(x-2)(x-4)\Rightarrow x=2\text{ or }x=4.\\ 0&=x^2+x-6=(x-2)(x+3)\Rightarrow x=2\text{ or }x=-3. \end{align}The only value of $x$ which makes both absolute values zero is $x=\boxed{2}$.
 *)
